, border walls and nationalisms are on the rise as people express desires to "take back" sovereignty. This collection uses ethnographic research in disputed and exceptional places to study sovereignty claims from the ground up. While it might immediately seem that citizens desire a stronger state, the cases of compromised, contested, or failed sovereignty in this volume point instead to political imaginations beyond the state form. Authors use cases from Spain to Afghanistan, Western Sahara to Taiwan, to show how calls to take back control or to bring back order are best understood as longings for sovereign agency. By paying close ethnographic attention to these desires and their consequences, The Everyday Lives of Sovereignty offers a new way to understand why these yearnings have such profound political resonance in a globally interconnected world.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aSovereignty. 4aAnthropology. 4aInternational Studies. 4aPolitical Science & Political History. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Constitutions.2bisacsh  aAnthropological perspectives on sovereignty, Daily life in unrecognized states, Everyday life at disputed borderlands, Everyday life in contexts of territorial dispute, sovereignty and ways of life.1 aAchniotis, Panos, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBartelson, Jens, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBryant, Rebecca, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBryant, Rebecca, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aDalsheim, Joyce, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDzenovska, Dace, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFriedman, State Sara L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHr